y by adapting their works to unconventional spaces and audiences, asserting artistic autonomy from art institutions, and embracing interdisciplinarity. In showing how these artists used art to question what art should be and where it should be seen, Woodruff demonstrates how artists challenged and redefined the art establishment and their historical moment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aArt criticismzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aArtxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aArt, FrenchxGovernment policyzFrance. 0aArts and societyzFrance. 0aArts, Moderny20th century. 0aGroupe de recherche d'art visuel. 0aInteractive artzFrance. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069631840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478090298zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478090298/original  a978-3-11-069631-8 Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA